docs.abstract: The return of a few thousand fans to Premier League stadiums was a reminder that it’s not only their roars that we’ve missed.
docs.snippet: The return of a few thousand fans to Premier League stadiums was a reminder that it’s not only their roars that we’ve missed.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — The stillness spoke volumes. There were 12 minutes left to play, but the game was over. Manchester United’s players were swarming around Marcus Rashford, scorer of his team’s third goal, the one that had settled matters. West Ham’s were staring blankly at the turf, unsure of quite how things had slipped away from them.

headline.main: As Premier League Gates Reopen, a Soothing Soundtrack Returns
headline.print_headline: The Premier League’s Soundtrack Is Back

docs.abstract: In the chaos of 1960s Detroit, a fledgling police union laid the groundwork for a system that, to this day, constrains discipline for officers accused of misconduct.
docs.snippet: In the chaos of 1960s Detroit, a fledgling police union laid the groundwork for a system that, to this day, constrains discipline for officers accused of misconduct.
docs.lead_paragraph: It took Portland, Ore., almost $1 million in legal fees, efforts by two mayors and a police chief, and years of battle with the police union to defend the firing of Officer Ron Frashour — only to have to bring him back. Today, the veteran white officer, who shot an unarmed Black man in the back a decade ago, is still on the force.

headline.main: How Cities Lost Control of Police Discipline
headline.print_headline: The Way Cities Lost Oversight Of Their Police

byline.original: By Kim Barker, Michael H. Keller and Steve Eder

docs.abstract: The friendship between Ricardo Allen, an undersized cornerback, and Matt Ryan, the heralded quarterback, has shaped the Falcons’ activism against racial injustice.
docs.snippet: The friendship between Ricardo Allen, an undersized cornerback, and Matt Ryan, the heralded quarterback, has shaped the Falcons’ activism against racial injustice.
docs.lead_paragraph: Six years later, the photo remains one of Ricardo Allen’s favorites. Standing in a Dick’s Sporting Goods, the Atlanta Falcons defensive back is smiling ear to ear, having just been promoted to the active roster after spending most of his rookie season on the practice squad. Matt Ryan, the team’s star quarterback, is walking into the frame to shake his hand.

headline.main: Talking About Race Made Two N.F.L. Teammates Partners in Activism

docs.abstract: His younger brother, a police officer, was assassinated by a drug gang at 22, a key moment in the city’s crack epidemic of the 1980s.
docs.snippet: His younger brother, a police officer, was assassinated by a drug gang at 22, a key moment in the city’s crack epidemic of the 1980s.
docs.lead_paragraph: Lawrence M. Byrne, who as the top lawyer for the New York City Police Department defended several hotly disputed police policies and who also kept alive the legacy of his brother, a rookie police officer who was executed by a drug gang, died on Dec. 6 in Manhattan. He was 61.

headline.main: Lawrence Byrne, Former Lawyer for New York Police, Dies at 61
headline.print_headline: Lawrence Byrne, Former Lawyer For New York Police, Is Dead at 61

docs.abstract: Amid the challenges of 2020, there are reasons to be optimistic heading into the new year.
docs.snippet: Amid the challenges of 2020, there are reasons to be optimistic heading into the new year.
docs.lead_paragraph: To say that 2020 was stressful is an understatement, what with a pandemic that the world hasn’t yet emerged from, a sharply divisive U.S. presidential election whose controversies have yet to ebb, social unrest over vast inequalities … need we go on?

headline.main: What We’re Looking Forward To in 2021
